T1  - Does the form of compensation matter?: Investment banker fee contracts in tender offers
AU  - McLaughlin, Robyn M.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
SP  - 223
EP  - 260
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(92)90019-T
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X9290019T
AB  - The role of fee contracts in the agency relation between investment bankers and client firms in tender offers is investigated using a sample of offers between 1978 and 1986. Different fees have different payoff functions which can be used by firms to create incentives and by bankers to signal differences in abilities. The effectiveness of fee contracts in resolving agency problems in tested, with mixed results. The evidence suggests that fee contracts are used as a tool by both firms and bankers and that contracts influence tender offer outcomes but that contracting is only a partial solution to the agency problem.
ER  - 
